“My suspicion is that any delay to Brexit is a plot to stop Brexit,” Conservative lawmaker Jacob Rees-Mogg tweeted.
ADThe prime minister promised Parliament it would have a “meaningful vote” on her Brexit deal by March 12 — about two weeks before the deadline to leave.
A British government report released on Tuesday assessed that a no-deal Brexit would disrupt trade, would probably increase prices on food and cars and could cost British businesses $17 billion a year.
Nine Labour lawmakers who support remaining in Europe resigned last week.
ADSeveral lawmakers asked how she would vote if, on March 13, there was indeed a chance to weigh in on whether to support a “no deal” Brexit.